You&#x27;d be surprised. I&#x27;m more familiar with k (kona) than J, but many of those seemingly inscrutable blocks of punctuation become recognizable as a unit pretty quickly. You can, of course, break huge expressions like that apart and name the chunks.<p>kona: <a href="https://github.com/kevinlawler/kona" rel="nofollow">https://github.com/kevinlawler/kona</a> A free implementation of a k3.2-like language.<p>There are equally strange patterns that you are probably used to. For example, I see stuff like<p><pre><code>    PORTB &=~(1<<3);
</code></pre>
when doing embedded development. That&#x27;s C, and unlike in J, in C I have to also keep track of order of operations.
